<TEXT>&#2;<DATELINE>2009-06-18</DATELINE><TITLE>Cancer Prevention Researchâ€“Then and Now</TITLE><BODY>Throughout history, human kind has won many battles against deadly diseases, including small pox, polio, tuberculosis and more recently severe acute respiratory syndrome. All of these diseases were defeated by prevention. Achieving cancer prevention is a global priority, but history tells us that the pathway to achievement is difficult and full of detours and roadblocks. Epidemiology and clinical evidence clearly indicate that specific factors are associated with an increased risk for cancer development. What can we learn from the past that is applicable to the reality of successful cancer prevention?&#3;</BODY></TEXT>